  "algorithm_explanation": {
    "overview": "Tipperary’s tip suggestion algorithm is a hybrid, context-aware system that combines crowdsourced user data, regional and restaurant-specific norms, and personal user behavior to generate accurate, actionable tipping ranges. Unlike one-size-fits-all calculators, it prioritizes granularity and real-world context to ensure suggestions align with both local etiquette and individual user preferences.",
    "core_data_sources": {
      "primary_crowdsourced_user_data": [
        "Verified tip submissions: Users input their total bill, tip amount, and a 1-5 service rating after dining. Submissions are verified via optional receipt uploads or integration with point-of-sale (POS) systems at partner restaurants to reduce fraudulent data.",
        "Contextual tags: Users can flag variables like party size, time of day (breakfast/lunch/dinner/late-night), special occasions (anniversaries, birthdays), or unique service events (e.g., \"server accommodated dietary restrictions\") that influenced their tip.",
        "Feedback on suggestions: Post-tipping, users rate whether the algorithm’s suggestion was \"too low,\" \"appropriate,\" or \"too high\"—this data directly refines future recommendations."
      ],
      "secondary_third-party_contextual_data": [
        "Restaurant metadata: Category (fine dining, casual, fast-casual, bar), location (city/state/country), and average bill value from platforms like Yelp, OpenTable, and Google Maps.",
        "Regional tipping norms: Aggregated data from government labor reports, industry surveys, and cultural etiquette databases to establish baseline ranges (e.g., 15-20% in the U.S., 10-15% in the U.K., no expected tip in Japan).",
        "Economic indicators: Local minimum wage for tipped workers (to adjust baselines—restaurants in areas with subminimum wage have higher expected tip ranges) and inflation rates (to update ranges quarterly)."
      ]
    },
    "step-by-step_algorithm_workflow": {
      "1_data_ingestion_and_preprocessing": "Raw data is cleaned and normalized to eliminate noise: \n- Outlier detection: Using the Interquartile Range (IQR) method, tip percentages outside Q1-1.5*IQR or Q3+1.5*IQR are flagged for manual review or excluded (e.g., a 0% tip for a 5-star service rating is discarded as likely error). \n- Currency conversion: All tip amounts are converted to a common currency (USD) for cross-region analysis, then converted back to the user’s local currency for output. \n- Credibility weighting: Submissions from users with 10+ verified tips are weighted 2x more heavily than first-time users to prioritize trusted data.",
      "2_feature_engineering_and_contextual_normalization": "Key features are derived to model tipping behavior: \n- Tip percentage (tip amount / total bill) to standardize across different bill sizes. \n- Service score deviation: How a user’s service rating compares to the restaurant’s average service score. \n- Contextual modifiers: Binary flags for party size (>6 guests = higher tip expectation in many regions), time of day (dinner tips are often 2-3% higher than lunch), and special occasions. \n- Regional baseline adjustment: The restaurant’s raw average tip is aligned with local norms (e.g., if a U.S. restaurant’s raw average is 14%, it’s adjusted upward to match the 15-20% regional baseline until more data is collected).",
      "3_aggregated_baseline_calculation": "A time-weighted average tip range is computed for each restaurant: \n- Recency weighting: Tips from the last 30 days are weighted 3x, 30-90 days 2x, and 90+ days 1x to reflect current service quality (e.g., a restaurant with a recent management change will prioritize new data over outdated submissions). \n- Confidence threshold: If a restaurant has fewer than 5 verified tips, the algorithm falls back to the regional category baseline (e.g., 18-20% for a fine dining restaurant in New York City) until more data is accumulated. \n- Final baseline range: The 25th to 75th percentile of weighted tip percentages is used to form the core suggestion range (e.g., 17-20% for a casual bistro with consistent service).",
      "4_personalization_layer": "The baseline range is adjusted to match the user’s unique behavior: \n- Tipping history: If a user consistently tips 2% above the average for similar restaurants, the range is shifted upward (e.g., 19-22% instead of 17-20%). \n- Preference settings: Users can set a \"generosity bias\" (e.g., \"always tip the upper end of ranges\") or accessibility needs (e.g., \"simplify suggestions to a single number\"). \n- Contextual alignment: If the user’s party size is 8+ (a common trigger for automatic gratuity), the algorithm flags this and suggests verifying if the restaurant includes a mandatory tip in the bill.",
      "5_output_generation_and_explanation": "The final suggestion is presented as a range with clear context: \n- Example output: \"18-21% is typical here. Recent users noted attentive service for large parties, so 20% is a well-received tip.\" \n- Optional breakdown: Users can tap to see how factors like regional norms, service ratings, and their own history influenced the range."
    },
    "accuracy_and_reliability_safeguards": {
      "outlier_detection_and_data_validation": "Automated checks flag submissions where the tip percentage is 5%+ outside the regional baseline (e.g., a 30% tip at a fast-casual restaurant) for user confirmation. Partner restaurants with POS integration provide real-time tip data to cross-verify crowdsourced submissions.",
      "model_validation_and_ab_testing": "The algorithm is tested weekly using historical data to ensure suggestions match 85%+ of user-reported \"appropriate\" tips. A/B tests are run with subsets of users to compare satisfaction rates between personalized ranges and generic calculators, with results used to refine feature weights.",
      "bias_mitigation": "Regular audits are conducted to avoid skewed suggestions for underrepresented restaurant types (e.g., minority-owned businesses). If a restaurant’s data shows a significant gap between average tips and service ratings, the algorithm flags it for review to rule out bias in user submissions.",
      "continuous_learning": "The model is retrained weekly with new data to update feature weights (e.g., increasing the impact of \"dietary accommodation\" tags if users consistently tip more for this service). Regional baselines are updated quarterly to reflect changes in minimum wage or cultural etiquette shifts."
    }
  }
}

